The color of the sky appears to vary depending on several factors including the time of day, weather conditions, and location. During the day, when the sun is high in the sky, the atmosphere scatters sunlight in all directions, but shorter (blue) wavelengths are scattered more than longer (red) wavelengths, which is why the sky often appears blue. During sunrise and sunset, the sky can appear red, orange, pink, or purple due to the scattering of sunlight at different angles and the presence of particles and pollutants in the atmosphere. At night, when the sun is below the horizon, the sky appears dark, but can be illuminated by artificial light sources or celestial objects such as the moon and stars. So, the color of the sky isn't fixed; it's a result of complex interactions between sunlight and the Earth's atmosphere.